<br>
From what I can tell it looks as though Rick has all but saved the forest rivers. No wonder he has been such a recluse for the last few months with this looming over his shoulder. <br>
<br>
The Forest Service has used a &quot;model&quot; for the last few decades that determined the effects of logging in the Ozark National Forest. The small mouth streams such as the Mulberry were the effect of such logging practices. Rick discovered some fatal mathematical flaws with this model that would not give a true picture of the effects of such logging. <br>
<br>
In summary Rick may have basically saved the streams in the Ozark National Forest single handedly from certain destruction. The more I find out about the issue the more I am impressed with Ricks fortitude and concern for the Ozarks. It seems as though he has put his career on the line for the sake of doing what is right. The article indicates that rick has endured considerable pressure to &quot;keep quiet&quot; and maintain the status quo.<br>
<br>
Thank you Rick for all your good works! I grew up fly fishing those streams. Keep us posted on the progress of the situation (if you can). It looks as though you have your hands full. Just know that we all support your efforts and you are not alone.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rickgolden@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Rick Golden</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Environment Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#000000>(7/8/03 7:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: </span><hr size=1> Thanks, John.  It has been a few tough months.  It appears that some members of the Ozark Forest managemnt staff may in fact be seeing a bit of light about the need to make a serious effort at understanding what is going on in the streams.  There are some excellent folks at the universities in Arkansas and surrounding states doing some very good research.  It appears that Ozark Forest managers are going to finally consider collaborating with them.  We may even start to implement the basics of a sound fish/hydrology program.  Nothing fancy, but it could grow into something sound over time.  It would be a great thing to see.  <br>
<br>
